				<div class="entry">

					<h2><a href="http://blog.mktgeist.com/2012/10/18/silver-and-gold-price-action-winter-outlook-wealthcycles/">Silver and Gold Price Action &#8211; Winter Outlook&nbsp;[wealthcycles]</a></h2>

					<div class="post-info">
						<p>
							<span class="time">October 18, 2012</span>
															<span class="author">by <a href="http://blog.mktgeist.com/author/mktgeistmike/" title="Posts by mktgeistmike" rel="author">mktgeistmike</a></span>
																						<span class="post-comments"><a href="http://blog.mktgeist.com/2012/10/18/silver-and-gold-price-action-winter-outlook-wealthcycles/#respond" title="Comment on Silver and Gold Price Action &#8211; Winter Outlook&nbsp;[wealthcycles]">Leave a comment</a></span>
																				</p>
					</div>

					<p>As markets never go anywhere in a straight line we have been licking our chops to explain to readers the small pull-back in silver and gold following a rally out of the summer consolidation period on new printing. Here is our projection for where we will head through early 2013 and why.</p>
<p>On July 17 veteran fund manager Marc FaberÂ <a href="http://www.marketwatch.com/story/how-bernanke-will-cause-the-next-crash-before-2014-2012-07-17?link=MW_story_popular">warned</a>Â that investors âmay lose up to 50 percent of their total wealth,â and said that âgold is oversold near-termâ after observing two months of consolidation under the 1650 pivot point. ForÂ <a href="http://youtu.be/SRcsVt0QqDk" target="_blank">GoldSilver Insiders</a>, Mike Maloney published videos at<a href="http://www.goldsilver.com/" target="_blank">GoldSilver.com</a>Â during the consolidation period, in which he said that âit is getting more bullish for gold and silver,â after commenting on the demoralized sentiment.</p>
<p>Citing little new web-based curiosity, Mike quipped that the âbull market hasnât even gotten going yet,â despite goldâs actual rise ever since 1934, from twenty bucks an ounce to where we sit today.</p>
<p>Alternatively we could have said: â&#8230;despite the Fedâs dollar fall in purchasing power since 1934, from twenty bucks to buy an ounce of gold, all the way down to where we sit today.â In July, Mike said he âjust does not think we have several months [more] before things start to move,â and that his preferred strategy was continuous diversification of savings into gold and silver.</p>
